preferred\nto MRI.\n3. CT is excellent in cases of intracranial hemorrahge.\n4. CT is favoured in the chest than MRI.\nContraindica tions of CT:\n1. CT scans are almost always avoided during pregnancy unless the benefits of the\ntest clearly outweigh the potential risks.\n2. A patient known iodine allergy\n3. A patient with hypothyroidism or an enlarged thyroid (goiter)\n4. In case of planned radioiodine treatment of thyroid cancer\nMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI)\nMechanism of action\n▪ Getting an image from MRI depends upon the presence of protons in the body.\n▪ Protons are free hydrogen atoms (proton without electrons). They are abundant\nin the body. With their net positive charge, protons are small magnets, each\nhaving a north and a south pole.\n▪ When placed in a strong magnetic field, enough of these tiny proton magnets\nalign to form a single magnetic vector. A radiofrequency pulse is added to this\nsteady state and tips the net magnetic vector off axis.\n▪ As the vector returns to its alignment in the magnet, energy is released. It is this\nenergy that is used to create the image.\nWhat is being imaged with MRI?\n▪ In general, MRI is water imaging.\n▪ Most pathologic conditions in the body are associated with edema, or water\nformation.\n6"}